  "memory_id": "cf4caab1-3ca9-4c73-b7d2-3b34528c6c38",
  "source": "corpus/Autonomousdrones-part-3.md",
  "preview": "[sandbox:corpus/Autonomousdrones-part-3.md chunk 2/3] flight controllers. The integration of safety features at th",
  "text": "flight controllers. The integration of safety features at the motor level enables a drone to attain ACL of level 3 with certainty [23]. The outer rotor permanent magnet brushless DC motor for drones can be improved by incorporating a Halbach magnet array. Design optimization techniques are introduced to enhance its power characteristics and reduce weight. The goal of the manufacturers is to achieve improved performance compared to the currently used commercial drone motor [24]. ## **Flight control and ESC** The Flight Controller (FC) is often referred to as the brain of the drone, which implements various operations in a drone. Most crucial operations of a flight controller are stabilizing the drone [25]. The flight controller consists of a microcontroller unit (MCU) with various sensors for feedback, the data from the same is processed by the microcontroller and respectively a signal based on the data is sent to Electronic Speed Controller (ESC) to control the BLDC drive [26]. ESC is a control circuit board connected with the BLDC motor to control the motor’s speed. The minimum operating frequency of an ESC is 50 Hz. An ESC controls the electric motor relative to the PWM signal it receives, which determines the speed of the motor [27]. The main sensor used in all the FC is the inertial measurement unit (IMU) sensor, which includes a 3-axis gyroscope, 3-axis accelerometer, 3-axis magnetometer, and a barometer [28]. As the sensor data is raw and not stable, multiple data processing filters are added to them, and an easy-to-implement filter is the Kalman filter [29]. Based on the data, analog signals are sent to the ESC, which further processes the signals and the voltage to the 3-phase BLDC motor. After processing the received feedback, the FC introduces corrections to minimize the error as much as possible. The most common method utilized for tuning the drone is Proportional Integral and Derivative (PID) algorithm [27]. It includes 3 constant parameters which are Proportional ‘P’ which represents current error, Integral ‘I’ represents accumulated error and Derivative ‘D’ that forecasts the forthcoming error [30]. PID helps introduce corrections based on errors between the reference and actual position allowing a stable flight time [30]. Beyond a stable flight, accurate control and dynamic yet precise manoeuvres with dynamically generated trajectories that are feasible and smooth become critical for complex applications [31]. Advancements in the microcontroller and microcontroller architecture of the flight-controllers allowed many",
  "metadata": {},
  "score": 0.6742882132530212
}